            <abstract id="ref49" label="Abstract">This collection includes Jane Hoffer's photographs and interviews of women police officers between 1975 and 1979. The photos were later included in an exhibition called 
                <emph render="italic">On the Beat 1975-1979: Women in the NYPD</emph>. An artist's book of the photos is also included.</abstract>
        </did>
        <arrangement id="ref1">
            <head>Arrangement note</head>
            <p>The photographs are arranged by subjects designated by the photographer. The non-photographic material (interviews, DVD, contact sheets and book) is foldered by format.</p>
        </arrangement>
        <relatedmaterial id="ref48">
            <head>Related Material at Other Institutions</head>
            <p>The New York City Police Museum also holds a collection of Jane Hoffer's photographs of police women.</p>
        </relatedmaterial>
        <bioghist id="ref2">
            <head>Biographical/Historical note</head>
            <p>Born in Canada, Jane Hoffer is a New York City based photographer who has been doing freelance work for over forty years. Hoffer attended McGill University where she started in painting and ended her graduate career with a dissertation on photographic essays. She received further training at the School of Visual Arts, the New School, and the International Center of Photography. Hoffer’s professional work has been primarily for non-profit organizations, including the Boys Choir of Harlem and Lincoln Center. In addition to her commercial work, Hofffer has pursued many artistic projects that have been exhibited throughout the city in both group and solo shows. SHe is currently a member of Professional Women Photographers.</p>
            <p>The photographs in this collection document some of the first women police officers out on patrol in New York City. President Lyndon Johnson’s Crime Commission in 1967 reccomended sweeping changes to law enforcement training and hiring practices and called for for “new kinds of people” within in police forces: college graduates, women, minorities and skilled civilians. More and more women became patrol officers and moved into supervisory positions like station supervisor and detective. Further studies like the Kerner Commision’s 1968 
                <emph render="italic">Report of the National Advisory Commission on Civil Disorders</emph> and psychologist and Ford Foundation director Catherine Miller’s 1972 study, 
                <emph render="italic">Women in Policing</emph>, contributed to the changing attitude toward women stepping out from behind the desk to take on more active policing duties. Policewomen faced fierce resistance from people outside their departments, as well as resentment from their fellow officers.</p>
            <p>Hoffer began the project in the 1970’s when she was teaching photography at John Jay College of Criminal Justice when the photography collective to which she belonged, Women Photographers of New York, began a series of projects on working women. A colleague introduced her to Sergeant Joan Pearson, who then acquainted her with other female officers who were willing to be interviewed and photographed. Fascinated by the emerging roles of women in police work, Hoffer photographed officers, sergeants, and auxillaries in precinct houses, their patrol cars, and at the firing range. She also conducted extensive interviews of her subjects. The process continued for four years.</p>
            <p>The photographs were exhibited at the SoHo Photo Gallery in 1980, the Wall Gallery at the John Jay College of Criminal Justice in 1989 and the New York City Police Museum in 2011, where the exhibit was called 
                <emph render="italic">On the Beat 1975-1979: Women in the NYPD</emph>. The work was also published as an artist’s book, 
                <emph render="italic">On the Beat 1975-79</emph>, which contains selections from the interviews as well as photographs.</p>
        </bioghist>
