        <scopecontent id="ref5">
            <head>Scope and Contents note</head>
            <p>This collection contains photographs and other materials relating to 
                <emph render="italic">On the Beat 1975-1979: Women in the NYPD</emph>, an exhibition of Hoffer’s photographs of some of the first female NYPD officers on the job. The photographs were taken between the years of 1975 to 1979. Photographs are arranged in the categories originally designated by the photographer, The subjects are named by the photographer as follows:</p>
            <p>AUXILLARIES are two mounted officers, Susan Cohen and Susan Cooke and are pictured riding and caring for their horses.</p>
            <p>COLLINS is Sergeant Barbara Collins who is depicted in her precinct, in dress blues, processing suspects and on patrol.</p>
            <p>DECOYS is photographs of officers disguised as vulnerable citizens to act as a plant to lure muggers. They are mostly of Officer Rita Kaplowitz, who is a part of the street crime unit. Photographs show her being disguised as an older woman, at the station, and speaking to senior citizens in costume.</p>
            <p>HARTMANN is Officer Mary Hartmann, who is shown assisting on EMT calls, turning out at roll call and on patrol in dress blues.</p>
            <p>KNEDLEHAN is Officer Helen Knedlehan, an emergency service officer and instructor who is depicted teaching first aid and using the jaws of life on a car.</p>
            <p>PEARSON is Sergeant Joan Pearson and is shown in the precinct house, on late night emergency calls, at the precinct cells and out on patrol doing “community relations.”</p>
            <p>STANTON is Sergeant Marcia Stanton who is shown answering disturbance calls, in the precinct house and doing her make up.</p>
            <p>SHAUGHNESSY is Officer Peggy O’Shaughnessy. She is shown at the shooting rage, on patrol, at the station, helping on an EMT call and in front of a burnt out building.</p>
            <p>VAL DORNAN is Officer Val Dornan who is photographed in the locker room.</p>
            <p>WALKER is shown on patrol and answering disturbance calls. Her first name and rank are not available.</p>
            <p>WILSON is Ann Wilson, a physical instructor at the Police Academy. Prints show her teaching self defense to men and women, working with police recruits and instructing physical training.</p>
            <p>There are 105 5x7” gelatin silver photographs, 26 11x14” gelatin silver photographers, and 8 contact sheets. The contact sheets includes images of “Women Partners,” for which there are no prints.</p>
            <p>In addition to photographic prints and contact sheets, there is 1 DVD containing photographs and interviews, and an artist’s book 
                <emph render="italic">On the Beat 1975-79</emph> which contains photos and selections from the interviews. The interviews themselves are with a selection of nine of the subjects of the photos.</p>
            <p>Note that some of the photographs in this collection are not represented in the book; there are also a few images that appear in the book but are not included in this collection.</p>
        </scopecontent>
